    "narrative": "For the April 13th slate, our primary objective is balancing the scarcity of stolen bases with the high-variance environments created by today\u2019s wind and favorable park factors. **Corbin Carroll** (85.64) is our clear standout, buoyed by a +16% park adjustment and a prime #2 hole placement that maximizes his speed-based scoring potential. Close behind in our tier of elite starts are **Jose Caballero** (67.93), **Gabriel Moreno** (67.29), and **Giancarlo Stanton** (66.92). **Jose Caballero** is particularly noteworthy; despite being relegated to the #9 spot, his +13% platoon edge against Yusei Kikuchi makes him a critical contributor, especially as we prioritize his stolen base upside against a pitcher who struggles to neutralize runners. **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (66.38) also benefit significantly from the Kikuchi matchup, with wind blowing out providing a tangible boost to their power projections.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved our bench, where **Max Muncy** (43.60) narrowly missed the cut. While **Max Muncy** carries respectable power, the optimizer ultimately favored the contact profiles of **Tyler Soderstrom** (55.72) and **Alex Freeland** (52.91). Although **Tyler Soderstrom** faces a tough arm in Nathan Eovaldi, his +10% park factor and the current lack of a better bench alternative kept him in the lineup over **Max Muncy**. We are keeping a close eye on the official lineups for **Gabriel Moreno**, **Dalton Rushing**, and **Austin Riley**; the latter remains a concern, as his matchup against Eury P\u00e9rez carries a -5% penalty due to the pitcher's elite skill set, requiring a perfect wind-aided environment to maintain his mid-50s scoring floor. We are proceeding with **James Wood** despite the extreme risk posed by Paul Skenes, as the projected volume of his #1 spot in the order outweighs the daunting -19% SP skill penalty.",
